[THUNDER]

00:33:27.341 --> 00:33:30.335
[GLASS BREAKING]

00:34:35.480 --> 00:34:38.719
- OK, following my research on
the Hollyhock House-- oh no--

00:34:38.719 --> 00:34:42.320
I see this piece very much in
dialogue with my sculptures,

00:34:42.320 --> 00:34:46.760
which frequently suggest
the presence of a body

00:34:46.760 --> 00:34:49.270
and trace history
through gesture

00:34:49.270 --> 00:34:51.820
Like the video about
Belterra and Alberta,

00:34:51.820 --> 00:34:53.659
this piece is an
attempt to excavate

00:34:53.659 --> 00:34:56.045
the unacknowledged
narratives contained

00:34:56.045 --> 00:34:58.220
in modernist buildings.

00:34:58.220 --> 00:35:01.280
Following my research
on the Hollyhock House,

00:35:01.280 --> 00:35:04.040
I became more and more
interested in the 1920s

00:35:04.040 --> 00:35:06.830
architectural trend of
Mayan revival buildings

00:35:06.830 --> 00:35:09.980
in the US, which
co-opted the architecture

00:35:09.980 --> 00:35:14.150
and iconography of pre-Columbian
Mesoamerican cultures.

00:35:14.150 --> 00:35:16.910
The style was popular
in Los Angeles,

00:35:16.910 --> 00:35:20.660
so I decided to focus on the
Mayan Theater, a Landmark Grand

00:35:20.660 --> 00:35:25.230
Cinema palace built during the
golden age of the movie-going.

00:35:25.230 --> 00:35:29.300
The interior design was done
by Mexican sculptor Francisco

00:35:29.300 --> 00:35:33.920
Cornejo, whose work specialized
in Maya and Aztec themes.

00:35:33.920 --> 00:35:36.320
I researched his sources--

00:35:36.320 --> 00:35:40.130
Quirigua and Piedras Negras
in Guatemala and Yaxchilan

00:35:40.130 --> 00:35:43.670
in the Yucatan in Mexico--

00:35:43.670 --> 00:35:46.150
and became fascinated
by the sophistication

00:35:46.150 --> 00:35:49.640
of ancient Mayan
architecture in regards

00:35:49.640 --> 00:35:53.630
to its performative quality
and relationship to the body.

00:35:53.630 --> 00:35:56.300
So I decided to make
a series of sculptures

00:35:56.300 --> 00:35:58.250
that would make
the beauty embody

00:35:58.250 --> 00:36:00.870
those qualities sculpturally.

00:36:00.870 --> 00:36:04.730
I made imprints of the reliefs
that decorate the Mayan Theater

00:36:04.730 --> 00:36:09.460
doors and walls with thick
swatches of silicone.

00:36:09.460 --> 00:36:11.900
The skin-like fragments
of architecture

00:36:11.900 --> 00:36:14.810
became elements of
assemblage of sculptures

00:36:14.810 --> 00:36:17.600
and were joined with
terracotta plaster casts

00:36:17.600 --> 00:36:21.350
of hands and feet locked
in gestures sourced

00:36:21.350 --> 00:36:23.900
from the original
archaeological sites,

00:36:23.900 --> 00:36:27.800
as well as bits of faux
Jaguar fur, quetzal feather,

00:36:27.800 --> 00:36:29.570
and serpent skin.

00:36:29.570 --> 00:36:31.280
I also tried to
bring a little bit

00:36:31.280 --> 00:36:33.470
of the information about
the source material

00:36:33.470 --> 00:36:36.020
through the titles.

00:36:36.020 --> 00:36:40.790
So, for instance,
in this work, which

00:36:40.790 --> 00:36:46.010
was "Yaxchilan Lintel
25 Feather Serpent,"

00:36:46.010 --> 00:36:50.600
I made an imprint of one
panel of an exit door that

00:36:50.600 --> 00:36:54.890
had an engraved based
on that specific lintel,

00:36:54.890 --> 00:36:58.010
more precisely the section
with the feather serpent,

00:36:58.010 --> 00:37:01.880
a Mayan supernatural entity,
and then the sculpture

00:37:01.880 --> 00:37:06.440
unfolded with relationships
with the body and the space.

00:37:09.350 --> 00:37:11.270
Another one, "Ha' Ki'n Xook--

00:37:11.270 --> 00:37:13.760
From Piedras Negras
to Hill Street,"

00:37:13.760 --> 00:37:15.965
tells you the name
of Piedras Negras

00:37:15.965 --> 00:37:20.510
ruler six, who was recreated
in the entrance hall

00:37:20.510 --> 00:37:23.910
doorway of the theater on
Hill Street in downtown LA.

00:37:33.920 --> 00:37:37.850
A two-headed serpent in the
arms of human beings, or ticket

00:37:37.850 --> 00:37:43.520
window, is also very descriptive
of the imagery appropriated

00:37:43.520 --> 00:37:45.732
and used around
the ticket window.

00:37:45.732 --> 00:37:46.940
And here you have just some--

00:37:46.940 --> 00:37:48.860
I don't expect you
to read that, again.

00:37:48.860 --> 00:37:51.860
It's just some indication
of my research.

00:37:58.320 --> 00:38:03.580
"The Heel Up in the Leg Cast
to Make the Building Dance"--

00:38:03.580 --> 00:38:07.750
this one is indicative
that a figure would

00:38:07.750 --> 00:38:11.620
be dancing in Mayan paintings
applied to vessels and murals,

00:38:11.620 --> 00:38:13.250
so the whole body
could be still.

00:38:13.250 --> 00:38:15.970
If a figure has
the heel up, that

00:38:15.970 --> 00:38:21.220
would mean that that
figure would be dancing,

00:38:21.220 --> 00:38:25.450
and the maize god, which
is painted on this plate,

00:38:25.450 --> 00:38:29.500
is usually portrayed
dancing with the heel up.

00:38:33.330 --> 00:38:35.930
"A Cycle of Time We
Don't Understand--

00:38:35.930 --> 00:38:38.910
Reverse, Invented,
and Rearranged"

00:38:38.910 --> 00:38:43.350
has a more elusive title that
relates to the glyphs created

00:38:43.350 --> 00:38:46.650
for the theater's entrance
floor that are mostly

00:38:46.650 --> 00:38:49.590
inspired by Calendrical glyphs.

00:38:49.590 --> 00:38:53.700
Mayan hieroglyphs would
never be placed on the floor,

00:38:53.700 --> 00:38:57.420
so I placed the swatches
of silicone on the wall,

00:38:57.420 --> 00:39:01.930
as it could have appeared
in a Mayan interior, usually

00:39:01.930 --> 00:39:05.030
around the borders of a
metalogical or historical

00:39:05.030 --> 00:39:05.530
scene.

00:39:10.260 --> 00:39:13.020
Another detail
important to point out

00:39:13.020 --> 00:39:17.190
is the repetition of the word
faux in the material list--

00:39:17.190 --> 00:39:21.690
faux terracotta dyed
plaster, jaguar faux fur,

00:39:21.690 --> 00:39:25.650
quetzal faux feather, died
rooster feather, faux serpent

00:39:25.650 --> 00:39:29.640
skin, and lastly,
synthetic hair.

00:39:29.640 --> 00:39:32.580
The insistence in
faux and synthetic

00:39:32.580 --> 00:39:35.820
was a way to suggest that
all the imagery contained

00:39:35.820 --> 00:39:39.160
on the silicone
imprints is also false.

00:39:39.160 --> 00:39:41.910
My intention was to restore
to the Mayan theater

00:39:41.910 --> 00:39:44.580
the immanence of
its source material

00:39:44.580 --> 00:39:47.650
while simultaneously
accentuating its design

00:39:47.650 --> 00:39:51.510
as a product of mimesis.

00:39:51.510 --> 00:39:54.300
OK, I will end just
saying a few words of what

00:39:54.300 --> 00:39:59.140
I am looking at right now.

00:39:59.140 --> 00:40:02.490
So, what I'm working
on at the moment

00:40:02.490 --> 00:40:06.300
is the very early stages
of a new installation that

00:40:06.300 --> 00:40:10.280
will further consider ecology
and Amazonian native people's

00:40:10.280 --> 00:40:12.540
static reduction
in the relationship

00:40:12.540 --> 00:40:16.740
to contemporary
commodity culture.

00:40:16.740 --> 00:40:21.390
The project will speculate on
a post-apocalyptic materiality

00:40:21.390 --> 00:40:24.620
that follows the Earth's
ecological collapse.

00:40:24.620 --> 00:40:28.290
What will remain when the Earth
as we know it is destroyed?

00:40:28.290 --> 00:40:29.910
In developing the
work, I've been

00:40:29.910 --> 00:40:34.170
inspired by Octavia E. Butler's
science fiction trilogy

00:40:34.170 --> 00:40:36.990
Lilith's Blood from 1989.

00:40:36.990 --> 00:40:38.760
For those of you who
don't know this book,

00:40:38.760 --> 00:40:40.710
I would explain very briefly--

00:40:40.710 --> 00:40:43.530
in Lilith's Blood,
the human race

00:40:43.530 --> 00:40:46.200
saves itself from
extinction by partnering

00:40:46.200 --> 00:40:49.070
with an alien
species, the Oankali.

00:40:49.070 --> 00:40:52.140
The Oankali's world is
made of living things,

00:40:52.140 --> 00:40:54.480
and that's what I'm interested--

00:40:54.480 --> 00:40:56.170
living things.

00:40:56.170 --> 00:41:00.000
There space ship is
structured like a rainforest

00:41:00.000 --> 00:41:02.520
and is fueled by food scraps.

00:41:02.520 --> 00:41:05.250
Their vehicles are
Oankali-made animals

00:41:05.250 --> 00:41:07.320
that respond telepathically.

00:41:07.320 --> 00:41:09.510
Their walls open
and close according

00:41:09.510 --> 00:41:11.460
to Oankali biochemistry.

00:41:11.460 --> 00:41:14.490
Eventually, the Amazon
Forest becomes the side

00:41:14.490 --> 00:41:18.990
of origin for a new civilization
of Oankali-human human hybrids.

00:41:18.990 --> 00:41:21.330
In Butler's
configuration, the Amazon

00:41:21.330 --> 00:41:25.790
is a site of second possibility,
and yet finite resources.

00:41:25.790 --> 00:41:28.590
I intended this new
body of work to inhabit

00:41:28.590 --> 00:41:32.400
an imaginary space of
post-Oankali-human occupation

00:41:32.400 --> 00:41:33.600
of Earth.

00:41:33.600 --> 00:41:35.370
My hope is to
create objects that

00:41:35.370 --> 00:41:38.790
teeter between the
prehistoric and futuristic--

00:41:38.790 --> 00:41:43.390
objects that seem ruins
of a world yet to come.

00:41:43.390 --> 00:41:46.090
I've been conducting research
at the Peabody Museum's

00:41:46.090 --> 00:41:48.570
Amazonian [INAUDIBLE]
ceramics collection,

00:41:48.570 --> 00:41:51.160
and you see two examples here.

00:41:51.160 --> 00:41:53.096
Especially there
are clay Monachinis

00:41:53.096 --> 00:41:58.350
that were at the
work-in-process exhibition

00:41:58.350 --> 00:42:02.130
that we had in January
here at the Radcliffe,

00:42:02.130 --> 00:42:04.100
and the funerary urns.

00:42:04.100 --> 00:42:07.410
I'm also expanding on my
understanding of Amazonian

00:42:07.410 --> 00:42:09.870
[FOREIGN],, basket
weave and practices,

00:42:09.870 --> 00:42:12.750
and indigenous Amazon
cosmology in general.

00:42:12.750 --> 00:42:15.960
I'm very interested in the
religious significance of trees

00:42:15.960 --> 00:42:18.780
and sacred animals, and
how those images are still

00:42:18.780 --> 00:42:24.160
used in Amazonian native
static traditions today.

00:42:24.160 --> 00:42:27.410
So I will leave it here.

00:42:27.410 --> 00:42:29.220
Thank you.

